anings":["Welsh, English:  see  Craddock  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Craddock","meanings":["Welsh and English: from the Welsh personal name <i>Caradawc</i>, <i>Cradawc</i>, <i>Caradoc</i>, <i>Caradog</i> meaning ‘amiable’, familiar in its Latin form <i>Caractacus</i> (but correctly <i>Caratacus</i>, for British Celtic <i>Caratācos</i>, from the stem <i>carat-</i> ‘dear, love’), a British prince who was taken as prisoner to Rome in about 51  AD  for his leadership of a revolt against the Roman occupation.","Americanized form of German   Gredig  . Compare   Graddick  ."]}]},{"name":"Wilcock","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (Lancashire and Yorkshire): from the Middle English personal name <i>Wilcoc</i>, a pet form of   William   (composed of the elements   Will   1 + the hypocoristic suffix <i>-cok</i>; see   Cocke  )."],"variants":[{"name":"Willcoxon","meanings":["English: patronymic from   Wilcock  ."]},{"name":"Wilcockson","meanings":["English (Derbyshire and Nottinghamshire): patronymic meaning ‘son of   Wilcock  ’."]},{"name":"William","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."]},{"name":"Wilcott","meanings":["English (Somerset and Gloucestershire): habitational name from Willicote in Clifford Chambers (Gloucestershire). The placename derives from Old English <i>wilig</i> ‘willow’ + <i>cot</i> ‘cottage, hut, shelter’. In some cases perhaps an altered form of   Wilcock  ."]},{"name":"Wilcox","meanings":["English (Yorkshire, Lancashire, and Flintshire): variant of   Wilcock  , with genitival or post-medieval excrescent <i>-s</i>. This form of the surname is based on the pronunciation."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Sir Wilcock Cradock was born about 1394, in Llansteffan, Carmarthenshire, Wales as the son of Agnes Russell. He had at least 4 daughters with Elen Ferch Jenkin. He died after 1429."},"et":{"about 1394–after 1429":"umbes 1394–pärast 1429","1394–1429":"1394–1429","1392–Female":"1392–Surnud","1417–1441":"1417–1441","1425–Female":"1425–Surnud","1426–1500":"1426–1500","1430–Female":"1430–Surnud","1365–Female":"1365–Surnud","Abt 1425":"umbes 1425","1394":"1394","1392":"1392","1426":"1426","1425":"1425","about 1417":"umbes 1417","1500":"1500","after 1429":"pärast 1429","1365":"1365","1430":"1430","1441":"1441","about 1430":"umbes 1430","1429":"1429","about 1394":"umbes 1394","1417":"1417","Llansteffan, Carmarthenshire, Wales":"Llansteffan, Carmarthenshire, Wales","Wales":"Wales, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"about 1394–after 1429":"noin 1394–1429 jälkeen","1394–1429":"1394–1429","1392–Female":"1392–Kuollut","1417–1441":"1417–1441","1425–Female":"1425–Kuollut","1426–1500":"1426–1500","1430–Female":"1430–Kuollut","1365–Female":"1365–Kuollut","Abt 1425":"noin 1425","1394":"1394","1392":"1392","1426":"1426","1425":"1425","about 1417":"noin 1417","1500":"1500","after 1429":"1429 jälkeen","1365":"1365","1430":"1430","1441":"1441","about 1430":"noin 1430","1429":"1429","about 1394":"noin 1394","1417":"1417","Llansteffan, Carmarthenshire, Wales":"Llansteffan, Carmarthenshire, Wales","Wales":"Wales, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"fr":{"about 1394–after 1429":"environ 1394–après 1429","1394–1429":"1394–1429","1392–Female":"1392–Décédée","1417–1441":"1417–1441","1425–Female":"1425–Décédée","1426–1500":"1426–1500","1430–Female":"1430–Décédée","1365–Female":"1365–Décédée","Abt 1425":"environ 1425","13